554
00:53:23,561 --> 00:53:32,006
So, we would want these to be floating units, because when applicants are when when tenants go over income, they don't get kicked out.

555
00:53:32,647 --> 00:53:35,128
They usually go up to I think 140% of airy mean income before.

556
00:53:39,129 --> 00:53:43,830
the units would change or convert to a market rate unit.

557
00:53:44,491 --> 00:53:56,514
So if an income eligible tenant was in the initial lease up and then they go over income, then it would revert to a market rate.

558
00:53:57,653 --> 00:54:02,177
And if they weren't floating units, then we wouldn't have, we'd be short an affordable unit.

559
00:54:02,797 --> 00:54:12,666
So what it would generally is in these regulatory agreements is that the next available or comparable unit would then become an affordable unit.

560
00:54:13,026 --> 00:54:16,269
So I always insist that they're floating.

561
00:54:16,609 --> 00:54:21,293
I've had developers want them to be fixed because that's advantageous to them.

562
00:54:21,313 --> 00:54:21,373
And

563
00:54:23,371 --> 00:54:28,295
floating is generally better for the city and to keep the units.

564
00:54:29,135 --> 00:54:45,066
And at the time, and again, I don't know about the comprehensive permit steps at this stage, but for local initiative program units, when we submit for those to be approved, that's when I would review the floor plans.

565
00:54:45,967 --> 00:54:52,732
And usually, you know, I make suggestions and ask that they be moved so that they're

566
00:54:53,987 --> 00:55:07,952
you know, proportionately distributed throughout the development, that, you know, it's the same, it's a percentage of the three, two, one, or studios for the bedrooms, and that they're not in the least desirable locations so that they're, you know, distributed.

567
00:55:08,932 --> 00:55:16,775
So there is staff input, and developers often change their floor plans at our requests.

568
00:55:18,809 --> 00:55:31,594
I would have to endorse that, Danielle that that is exactly the way it works, that the units need to be able to float so you don't end up with someone or household whose income exceeds 140% of AMI and now they have to leave.

569
00:55:34,175 --> 00:55:35,795
That's just not in anybody's interest.

570
00:55:35,835 --> 00:55:40,337
